A3: Incarceration

Introduction

An introduction of the problem domain and a description of the variable(s) you are choosing to analyze (and why!)

The problem domain of incarceration in America is a significant issue with a great number of its population behind bars. Ill be analyzing the total population of people in America incarcerated, comparing the differences between states/counties and how a persons demographic such as race may play a role as a significant amount of the people behind bars are part of the Black community. Im analyzing these variables, such as total_prison_pop, total_black_prison_pop, male_prison_pop, female_prison_pop, black_male_prison_pop, black_female_prison_pop to gain insights to potential trends that may be occurring and see if theres correlation between variables such as race.

The Dataset

Who collected the data?

The Vera Institute.

How was the data collected or generated?

This data was generated/provided by the Vera Institute from data that was already collected by the U.S. Department of Justice Bureau of Justice Statistics(BJS) which covers all jails and is collected every 5-8 years, the Death in Custody Reporting Program (DCRP) which collects data from about 2800 local jails every year since 2000, and the Annual Survey of Jails who covers about 1/3 of jails since 1985.

Why was the data collected?

The data was collected to expose patterns of inequality regarding incarceration injustice thats influences by variables such as ones demographic.

How many observations (rows) are in your data?

There are 153811 rows of observations in my data.

How many features (columns) are in the data?

There are 36 features in my data.

What, if any, ethical questions or questions of power do you need to consider when working with this data?

Some potential ethical questions or questions of power we need to consider when working with this data is privacy. Working with incarceration data is sensitive as for example that individual may not want information about their incarceration to be collected in data and shared with the public. Additionally, we should question if bringing things such as demographics such as race or gender may instill stereotypes and have the public react a certain way when said stereotypes arent accurate for everyone such as how the Black community contributes to a significant amount of the people in prison doesnt mean that the majority of Black people are dangerous. Since such idea is influencing the public, when going forward, officers may treat Black people less well just because of their race.

What are possible limitations or problems with this data? (at least 200 words)

Possibly limitations or problems when working with this data could include issues such as not having context or sufficient information about the incarceration. For example, we dont know the severity of each incarceration. Maybe one was for underage drinking and the other was for a robbery or a worse crime than that. But regardless, we dont know the extent of the crime and were categorizing them all in the same features. My variable was the black_prison_pop. So for example, maybe a lot of the incarcerations there were for underage drinking but due to things such as bias from officers, they were more likely to be arrested than maybe a white individual. Since this data is online, there could always be collecting/reporting issues. Whether caused by human error or a glitch in the system, there could be factors that skew the data. In other cases, maybe there was bias when the officer was reporting the case and lied due to their own opinions and views rather than the case itself. For example, if it is a white officer who views Black people as dangerous, hes more likely to exaggerate the severity of the case if he is arresting a black male.

Trends Over Time Chart

Include a chart. Make sure to describe why you included the chart, and what patterns emerged

The first chart that you will create and include will show the trend over time of your variable/topic. Think carefully about what you want to communicate to your user (you may have to find relevant trends in the dataset first!). Here are some requirements to help guide your design:

  • Show more than one, but fewer than ~10 trends
    • This may mean showing the same measure for different locations or different racial groups. Think carefully about a meaningful comparison of locations (e.g., the top 10 counties in a state, top 10 states, etc.)
  • You must have clear x and y axis labels
  • The chart needs a clear title
  • You need a legend for your different line colors and a clear legend title

When we say clear or human readable titles and labels, that means that you should not just display the variable name.

The total for each state is the sum of all the prison populations for each county within that state. There is a legend on the left side that represents the prison population and the greater the population, the darker the shade of purple and the smaller the population, the lighter the purple/approaching white. The patterns that emerged is that the states typically with a greater population had a greater total prison population compared to states with a smaller total population which makes sense as crime is more likely to happen in areas with more people.
